com.itko.lisaint

Class TransInfo

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.itko.lisaint.LisaCollector
      • com.itko.lisaint.CompInfo
        • com.itko.lisaint.TransInfo
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IReport

    public class TransInfo
extends CompInfo
    The TransInfo class contains all the information that can be gathered about the execution of a specific "transaction" of the system under test. This object is constructed by the Integrator on the server side by a test-enabled server component. It's read-write methods are used to inform the running test case of the status of this transaction. The Lisa instance that has requested this transaction will also get this object, either by deserializing or some other means. It will access only the read methods. Note that the definition of transaction is very loose. A transaction should map to a round-trip from the simulated user that Lisa is performing. Transactions can be broken up into sub-secitions and reported at that level with the CompInfo object. In fact, this TransInfo class is a CompInfo with but a few addional capabilities. To construct one of these, the compnent developer should call Integrator.startTransaction
    See Also:
    Integrator.startTransaction(java.lang.String), CompInfo

      • setNextNode

        public void setNextNode(java.lang.String forcedNode)
        Server component authors have the ability to instruct Lisa to execute a node of a given name explicitly. In general, this feature allows the test case to be driven by the server. This would obviously require that the server component author be aware of the test case node names. This is not often feasible. In the cases that are feasible, such as when a standard set of node names are used to test the component, this can be very powerful. Also, the name set here can actually be a Lisa property key. Put the key brace notation if it is a Lisa property key. For example, when the server component happens to hit a very rare condition that should be especially tested, then the server component can ensure that the condition is properly tested by calling this method and prescribing to the test case author this condition.
        Parameters:
        forcedNode - the Lisa node name that the server wants invoked next in the test case

      • failTest

        public void failTest(java.lang.String failTestMsg)
        Server components can instruct Lisa to end the test running with a failure. This has the effect of causing an ABend TestNode to be invoked automatically. This is a very useful feature in that many scenarios can be played out with the server's awareness. For example, a load test can be performed and the test failed from the server side if it runs out of resources. This takes the guess work out of the test case authoring.
        Parameters:
        failTestMsg - a string that will be logged and used by the test case author to better understand the reason for the failure
